      <hedline>
        <hl1>Children's Health Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John Glasel letter says October 17 editorial on New York State's enrollment mixup between Child Health Plus and Medicaid highlights problems posed by programs designed only for lower-income people</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>New York State's enrollment mix-up between Child Health Plus and Medicaid (editorial, Oct. 17) highlights the problems posed by programs designed only for lower-income people. Medicaid has long been a turnoff for many who have trouble dealing with its complex application requirements.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>New York State's enrollment mix-up between Child Health Plus and Medicaid (editorial, Oct. 17) highlights the problems posed by programs designed only for lower-income people. Medicaid has long been a turnoff for many who have trouble dealing with its complex application requirements.</p>
        <p>Now even state administrators are having trouble dealing with the overly bureaucratic dual system for poor children.</p>
        <p>Some might assert that this gives credence to their ''government works poorly'' ideology. Others will point out that the system of private insurance and health maintenance organizations isn't simple, either.</p>
        <p>Comptroller H. Carl McCall's suggestions for smoothing the bumps in the two systems might help a little. But wouldn't a system of universal health care be easier for everyone?</p>
        <p>JOHN GLASEL  Hoboken, N.J., Oct. 17, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is recording secretary, Health Care for All, New Jersey.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
